 - Bug Report


##### OS
```
CentOS 7.3
```
##### VERSION
```
ExaBGP : 4.0.2-1c737d99
Python : 2.7.5 (default, Nov  6 2016, 00:28:07)  [GCC 4.8.5 20150623 (Red Hat 4.8.5-11)]
```
##### ENVIRONMENT 
```
[exabgp.daemon]
pid = '/var/run/exabpg.pid'
user = 'root'

[exabgp.log]
destination = '/var/log/exabgp.log'

[exabgp.tcp]
bind = '[118.184.xxx.xxx]'
```

##### CONFIGURATION

```
process announce-routes {
    run /usr/bin/socat stdout pipe:/var/run/exabgp.cmd;
    encoder json;
}


template {
    neighbor router {
        router-id 118.184.xxx.xxx;
        local-address 118.184.xxx.xxx
        local-as 18257;
        peer-as 18257;

        group-updates false;
        hold-time 180;
        capability {
            graceful-restart 1200;
        }

        family {
            ipv4 unicast;
            ipv4 flow;
        }

        api {
            processes [ announce-routes ];
        }
    }
}

neighbor 61.160.xxx.xxx {
    inherit router;
}
```



##### SUMMARY


we announce following two flowspec route to exabgp, and find the later route will overwrite the first router instead of announcing two flowspec router.

```
echo "announce flow route { match { destination  118.184.169.141/32; } then { rate-limit 1000000000; redirect 65001:120; } }" > /var/run/exabgp.cmd

echo "announce flow route { match { destination  118.184.169.141/32; } then { discard; } }" > /var/run/exabgp.cmd
```

and withdraw command will withdraw previous announce router.

```
echo "withdraw flow route { match { destination  118.184.169.141/32; } then { rate-limit 1000000000; redirect 65001:120; } }" > /var/run/exabgp.cmd

echo "withdraw flow route { match { destination  118.184.169.141/32; } then { discard; } }" > /var/run/exabgp.cmd
```

the two router are same in rule and different in action. we should handle it different router.

now exabgp regard them same routers.

According to the docs this is how filtering works:
https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene-django/blob/master/docs/filtering.rst#custom-filtersets

However if I have a `ManyToMany` or `ForeignKey` related field.. it stops working!

This works:
```
query Tasks {
  tasks(search: "test") {
    edges {
      node {
        id
        ...Fields
      }
    }
  }
}
```

This does not work:
```
query ProjectTasks {
  projects {
    edges {
      node {
        id
        tasks(search: "test") {
          edges {
            node {
              id
              ...Fields
            }
          }
        }        
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Error message: `"message": "Unknown argument \"search\" on field \"tasks\" of type \"TaskNode\"."`

Possible reason:
The reason is that the related field gets resolved to a TaskNode and only `DjangoConnectionFields` currently allow custom FilterSets. Nodes only feature filter_fields. :|

@do3cc did an amazing job this last week to spot why Plone tests fail when [bumping zope.testrunner from 4.4.4 to 4.4.10](https://github.com/plone/buildout.coredev/pull/155): mixing ZopeTestCase based tests and plone.app.testing ones makes both step in each others stacks, thus breaking the setup/teardown contract.

As ZopeTestCase is way more old, it would be handy to have a debug mode that lists all tests that a layer based on ZopeTestCase.

Would a pull request that goes in that direction be accepted?

